<TITLE> HC asks govt, EC to explain no-elections in CHT </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 6 (bdnews24.com)The High Court on Wednesday asked the government and the Election Commission why elections to the Chittagong Hill Tracts Regional Council and Rangamati, Khagrachhari and Bandarban district councils would not be held. The court also them to explain why it was not illegal to not hold elections to Rangamati, Khagrachhari and Bandarban following the constitution of the regional council in 1998 and the first election of the councils in 1989. The bench of justices Syed Rifat Ahmed and Mainul Islam Chowdhury gave the local government secretary, CHT affairs secretary, Election Commission secretary and Chittagong divisional commissioner four weeks to reply. The orders came on a writ petition filed in the form of public interest litigation on Tuesday by Md Kamal Hossain, a resident of Rangamati and president of the CHT students forum. Advocate Tajul Islam said in the hearing the tenure of the CHT Regional Council, under section 12 of CHT Law was five year and there was compulsion to hold the election 60 days before the tenure ended. But, he further said, despite the formation of the first regional council in 1998, there had been no election to date. Similarly, despite compulsion to hold elections to Rangamati, Khagrachhari and Bandarban district councils under sections 4(2) and 16(1) of the 1989 law, no election was held after the only election in 1989. Islam said successive governments ran the CHT administration through unelected interim Parishads of their choice. As a result, the hills people were deprived of their right to vote. The interim parishads did not provide scope for representation of all tribal communities and other people and so, fundamental rights of the people of that area were violated, he added. b
